\f2\fs21 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 I'm thinking through the design system for noixzy's generative lab interface\'97a unified engine with a left-side module switcher, full-width canvas, grouped controls, and theming capabilities. I want to establish a cohesive token system and build an interactive prototype that captures noixzy's distinctive aesthetic: dark, moody, art-forward, and restrained. I'm starting to define what makes the visual direction distinctive for this platform.\cb1 \
\cb3 The key is avoiding generic AI defaults and instead creating something that feels like a lab instrument crossed with an art darkroom. The module switcher becomes the vertical spine of the interface, and the control panel functions as a precise instrument cluster with monospace data readouts for seed, fps, and dimensions. For the palette, I'm using a deep desaturated near-black with a subtle warm or cool undertone\'97not pure black\'97paired with off-white text. The clever part is making the accent color dynamic: instead of one fixed color, it's driven by the active theme, so the accent shifts with whatever theme is selected. I'll use CSS variables to handle this theming system. For typography, I'm pairing a characterful display font with a clean monospace utility font to balance personality with precision. Sketching out the interface structure with a top bar containing the noixzy wordmark, navigation breadcrumbs, and control buttons, flanked by a module list rail on the left and a properties panel on the right, with the main canvas area taking up the center space. cher, plus a theme toggle. The bottom bar shows shortcuts and format presets for aspect ratios, along with recording status.\cb1 \
\cb3 For the signature touch, I'm thinking the left rail modules should each display a tiny live generative glyph instead of just text\'97making it a living index that feels connected to the gallery concept. I'll also add a central canvas with subtle animated particles or a flow field so the interface feels alive rather than static. The whole thing should be genuinely interactive: clicking a module updates the active state, refreshes the canvas placeholder,\cb1 \
\cb3 Writing the interactive layer... The default accent will be a muted ember-orange that evokes a darkroom safelight, then the theme system cycles through teal, violet, steel, magenta, and acid-green to showcase the flexibility. I'm keeping the accent restrained\'97just one highlight per module like active states, slider fills, and focus rings\'97so everything else stays quiet. For typography, I'm setting up a modest scale with the wordmark prominent in the topbar, module names around 13px, and labels in mono uppercase at 10-11px with tracking. Now I'm working on custom slider styling...\cb1 \
\cb3 Writing custom CSS... More control groups for depth displacement, frame transforms, visual effects, and motion parameters. I'll make these collapsible with system and look expanded by default to avoid overwhelming the interface. The action row goes in the top-right with seed, pin, copy, paste, save, and other quick controls, while the bottom shows format presets for aspect ratios plus performance metrics.\cb1 \
\cb3 I'm wiring up the interactions now: clicking modules sets them active and updates the canvas, theme cycling swaps the accent color with animation, sliders show live values, group headers toggle collapse states, and keyboard shortcuts like\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf8 \cb9 \strokec8 h
\f2\fs21 \cf6 \cb3 \strokec6 \'a0hide the panel for a clean view while\'a0
